result.execSummary:
The defendant Joshua Paisley was found guilty of the following charge(s) in this case.

  • Battery [Modifiers: Domestic Abuse Assessments], a class A misdemeanor, Wisconsin Statutes 940.19(1).

Notice to employers: It may be a violation of state law to discriminate against a job applicant because of an arrest or conviction record. Generally speaking, an employer may refuse to hire an applicant on the basis of a conviction only if the circumstances of the conviction substantially relate to the particular job. For more information, see Wisconsin Statute 111.335 and the Department of Workforce Development's publication, Arrest and Conviction Records under the Law.

miscConds.notes:
-  Defendant to pay all applicable costs, assessments and surcharges, including the DV surcharge from bail on deposit.  If there is no posted bail the defendant is to pay the costs and surcharges during the period of probation. Failure to pay the costs and surcharges will result in a civil judgment.
- Pay supervision fees.

- No contact with victim unless approved by the court.  Defendant may have 3rd party contact for time with the child/ren with an agency approved by the probation agent.
- Court advised defendant of penalties for violating the no contact order.

- Complete batterer's intervention program.
 - Mental health evaluation; take all prescribed medications.
- Attend treatment and/or counseling as determined.

- AODA assessment; comply with any treatment.
- Maintain absolute sobriety; random urine screens.

- No contact with firearms.
- Court advised defendant that due to this DV conviction s/he may never possess firearms or ammunition.

Defendant Joshua Paisley in court with attorney Joel Alan Mogren.  Defendant Joshua Paisley in custody.  Andrea L Fendry appeared for the State of Wisconsin.
cab
  Defendant was advised of constitutional rights and maximum penalties, waived all rights, and plead GUILTY.  Defendant examined as to the plea.  Plea Questionnaire/Waiver of Rights and Addendum received and filed.  Stipulation by parties to complaint as a factual basis to sustain the plea.  Court found the defendant guilty. Judgment of conviction entered.
.
Sentencing continued...
.
  Statements by each counsel and defendant as to sentencing.  Additional statement/s by: Christine R.
Court sentenced the defendant to serve 6 months in the House of Correction with credit for 71 days served. 
 Court STAYED the sentence and placed the defendant on probation for 18 months with the following conditions:
- Serve 30 days in the House of Correction; STAYED pending review.
- Complete batterer's intervention program.
 - Mental health evaluation; take all prescribed medications.
- AODA assessment; comply with any treatment.
- Maintain absolute sobriety; random urine screens.
- Attend treatment and/or counseling as determined.
- No contact with victim unless approved by the court.  Defendant may have 3rd party contact for time with the child/ren with an agency approved by the probation agent.
- Obtain/maintain employment.
- No contact with firearms.
-  Defendant to pay all applicable costs, assessments and surcharges, including the DV surcharge from bail on deposit.  If there is no posted bail the defendant is to pay the costs and surcharges during the period of probation. Failure to pay the costs and surcharges will result in a civil judgment.
- Pay supervision fees.
